24
00:01:02.600 --> 00:01:06.400
And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new vocabulary as well.

25
00:01:06.400 --> 00:01:07.200
Great.

26
00:01:07.200 --> 00:01:10.000
But first, I have a question for you, Neil.

27
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.400
The reason it's difficult to know how much salt you consume

28
00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:17.200
is that it's hidden in a food, especially processed food.

29
00:01:17.200 --> 00:01:22.200
So which of the following everyday foods do you think contains most salt?

30
00:01:22.200 --> 00:01:26.800
Is it a, meat, be, bread, or sea, pasta?

31
00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:31.600
Well, I'm going to guess that meat is the saltiest of those foods.

32
00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:32.600
OK, Neil.

33
00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:35.600
I'll reveal the answer later in the program.

34
00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:40.000
Marion, some beaver, lives in a stana, the capital of Kazakhstan.

35
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.800
A country where people eat on average 17 grams of salt a day.

36
00:01:44.800 --> 00:01:49.400
That's more than three times the amount recommended by the WHO.

37
00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:52.800
Here, Marion explains some of the reasons behind this,

38
00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:56.000
to BBC World Service Program, the Food Chain.

39
00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.200
We consume lots of salt, which is due to historical heritage,

40
00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:05.800
because when we were nomads for centuries and centuries,

41
00:02:05.800 --> 00:02:09.800
we traveled the and wandered across the steps.

42
00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:13.800
And here we had to carry lots of meat,

43
00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:17.400
which could be preserved only at insult.

44
00:02:17.400 --> 00:02:20.800
And even the milk products, the dairy products,

45
00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:24.800
are also very much salty for the same reasons.

46
00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:29.000
Besides improving its flavor, salt can be used to preserve food,

47
00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:31.000
to stop it from going bad.

48
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.200
Traditionally, people in Kazakhstan were nomads.

49
00:02:34.200 --> 00:02:40.200
They traveled from place to place with their animals rather than living in one place all the time.

50
00:02:40.200 --> 00:02:45.000
Treating food with salt gave them enough to eat during the long winter months.

51
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:49.400
They even did it with dairy products, foods which are made from milk,

52
00:02:49.400 --> 00:02:51.200
such as cheese and butter.

53
00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:54.600
So, salt has a long and useful history,

54
00:02:54.600 --> 00:02:58.000
but there's a big difference between traditional Kazakh nomads

55
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.200
and the health problems associated with modern processed food.

56
00:03:02.200 --> 00:03:06.600
When we eat too much salt, the body dilutes it by retaining water.

57
00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:11.000
And as a result, the heart works harder to pump liquid around the body.

58
00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:16.200
This causes high blood pressure, which over time can lead to heart disease.

59
00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:20.600
Globally, governments are fighting this health risk in different ways.

60
00:03:20.600 --> 00:03:25.400
The Australian government reduced its recommended salt intake to six grams a day.

61
00:03:25.400 --> 00:03:31.200
While the British government has passed laws forcing food companies to reduce the amount of salt they use.

62
00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:34.600
And now, recommends just five grams of salt per day.

63
00:03:34.600 --> 00:03:39.800
Clark Orleans is Professor of Nutrition at the University of Newcastle in Australia.

64
00:03:39.800 --> 00:03:46.400
Here, she explains more about these salt recommendations to BBC World Service Program, the Food Chain.

65
00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:51.000
I think you just got to take a step back and look at the bigger picture.

66
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:54.200
Like arguing whether it should be five grams or six grams,

67
00:03:54.200 --> 00:04:00.600
the issue is that around the world, salt intakes a very high contributing to blood pressure,

68
00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:04.800
contributing to premature strokes, premature mortality,

69
00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:12.200
and we need to address it in a way that's culturally appropriate for each country.

70
00:04:12.200 --> 00:04:14.680
Instead of arguing over grams of salt,

71
00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:19.400
Professor Collins thinks we should take a step back and look at the bigger picture.

72
00:04:19.400 --> 00:04:25.720
She uses two idioms, take a step back, which means to temporarily withdraw from a situation

73
00:04:25.720 --> 00:04:28.400
in order to think about it more calmly.

74
00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:30.600
And look at the bigger picture.

75
00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:34.400
To consider the overall meaning of something, not just the details.

76
00:04:34.400 --> 00:04:40.600
Yes, the problem remains that overconsumption of salt is causing premature health problems,

77
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:43.800
which are happening sooner than they should.

78
00:04:43.800 --> 00:04:46.200
By limiting salt and process food,

79
00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:49.200
most people can enjoy long, healthy lives.

80
00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:54.200
And if you don't like your food unsalted, try adding herbs and spices instead.

81
00:04:54.200 --> 00:04:59.800
Well, speaking of salty foods, I think it's time to reveal the answer to my question, Neil.

82
00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:04.800
If you remember, I asked you which everyday food contains most salt.

83
00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:06.600
And I guessed it was meat.

84
00:05:06.600 --> 00:05:09.000
Which was the correct answer.

85
00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:13.800
Meat contains the highest amount of salt, around 19%.

86
00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:18.600
Followed by bread with 14% and pasta with 7%.

87
00:05:18.600 --> 00:05:22.200
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned in this program,

88
00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:25.000
starting with the verb to preserve food,

89
